&= \frac{\cos x + \cos x \sin x - \cos x + \cos x \sin x}{1 - \sin^2 x} \\
&= \frac{2\cos x \sin x}{1 - \sin^2 x}
\end{align*}

Now, we can use the fact that $\sin^2 x + \cos^2 x = 1$ to simplify further:

\begin{align*}
\frac{2\cos x \sin x}{1 - \sin^2 x} &= \frac{2\cos x \sin x}{(1 - \sin^2 x)(1)} \\
&= \frac{\cos x \sin x}{\frac{1-\sin^2 x}{2}} \\
&= 2\cos x \sin x
\end{align*}

